{"attack": true, "target_alias": "A1", "cited_input_aliases": ["A1"], "claim": "The target's mechanism fails to account for the survival of the Cypriot urban centers (e.g., Enkomi) which were part of the same interconnected Eastern Mediterranean system, relied on rain-fed agriculture, and experienced destruction layers c. 1220-1190 BC but were rapidly rebuilt and flourished in the 12th century BC.", "grounds": "The target's scope explicitly lists 'Mycenaean Greece, Hittite Anatolia, Ugarit, Levantine city-states' as the entities that collapsed, but the interconnected Eastern Mediterranean system also included Cyprus. Cypriot centers like Enkomi and Kition were integral to the Late Bronze Age trade network, relied on rain-fed agriculture, and yet they survived the initial crisis and experienced a period of prosperity after the collapse of the other palace systems. If the mechanism was a climatic shock that specifically targeted rain-fed agricultural hinterlands to trigger internal revolt, Cyprus should have collapsed as well, or at least not flourished. The target's mechanism is therefore undercut by a counterexample within the very system it purports to explain.", "counterexample": ["Cyprus (Alashiya)"]}